\mt1 Proverbs of Solomon
\c 1
\v 1 The proverbs of Solomon, son of David, who reigned in Israel.
\q1
\v 2 They give wisdom and instruction
\q2 so that one may understand knowledge,
\q1
\v 3 may have subtlety of speech and discern true righteousness
\q2 and judge justly,
\q1
\v 4 and so that one may give understanding to the simple
\q2 and perception and insight to the young.
\q1
\v 5 By studying these a wise man will become wiser,
\q2 and the knowledgeable man will gain direction.
\q1
\v 6 He will be able to understand parables and difficult sayings,
\q2 and also the teaching of the wise and deep mysteries.
\q1
\v 7 Fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom
\q2 and it gives depth of understanding to all those who practise it.
\q1 Godliness is the beginning of perception,
\q2 but the ungodly set at nothing wisdom and instruction.
\q1
\v 8 My son, listen to the teaching of your father
\q2 and do not reject your mother’s instructions,
\q1
\v 9 for you will receive a crown of graces upon your head
\q2 and a golden chain around your neck.
\q1
\v 10 My son, do not let the ungodly lead you astray,
\q2 nor agree with them
\v 11 when they entice you, saying,
\q1 ‘Come with us, let us shed blood for no good reason
\q2 and bury an innocent man in the ground.
\q1
\v 12 As Hades swallows the living,
\q2 let us swallow him and take away his memory from the earth.
\q1
\v 13 Let us seize his valuables
\q2 and fill our homes with the spoils.
\q1
\v 14 Cast your lot in with us
\q2 and let us all have one purse and a common wallet.’
\q1
\v 15 Do not follow their ways
\q2 but walk away from their paths,
\q1
\v 16 for their feet run towards iniquity
\q2 and they are quick to shed blood.
\q1
\v 17 Not without good reason
\q2 are nets spread to catch birds.
\q1
\v 18 By indulging in murder they store up evil for themselves,
\q2 for the downfall of transgressors is terrible.
\q1
\v 19 This is the destiny of all who do evil deeds,
\q2 for by ungodliness they destroy their own soul.
\q1
\v 20 Wisdom sings aloud in the streets;
\q2 she strides boldly in the squares.
\q1
\v 21 She preaches from the top of the walls;
\q2 she takes her seat at the gates of the mighty,
\q2 at the gates of the city she speaks boldly.
\q1
\v 22 The simple cling to righteousness,
\q2 and they will not be ashamed.
\q1 But the foolish, who delight in arrogance and have become ungodly,
\q2 hate wisdom
\v 23 and are liable to censure.
\q1 I shall take breath to speak out
\q2 and to teach you my word,
\q1
\v 24 for when I called you did not listen,
\q2 and when I spoke at length you ignored me.
\q1
\v 25 You have set at nothing my counsels
\q2 and given no attention to my warnings.
\q1
\v 26 Therefore I shall laugh at your destruction
\q2 and rejoice when ruin comes upon you.
\q1
\v 27 Yes, when unrest comes upon you suddenly
\q2 and your downfall strikes like a tempest,
\q1 and when trouble and siege descend upon you
\q2 or ruin faces you,
\q1
\v 28 you will find when you call upon me
\q2 that I shall not listen to you.
\q1 The wicked will seek me
\q2 but not find me
\q1
\v 29 because they hated wisdom
\q2 and did not choose the word of the Lord,
\q1
\v 30 nor would they pay attention to my advice
\q2 but despised my correction.
\q1
\v 31 Therefore they eat the fruits of their own actions
\q2 and are filled with their own ungodliness.
\q1
\v 32 Because they have wronged the simple they shall be destroyed,
\q2 and scrutiny will be the undoing of the ungodly.
\q1
\v 33 But the one who listens to me shall live in hope
\q2 and be at peace without fear of evil.
\c 2
\q1
\v 1 My son, if you will accept my words of instruction
\q2 and cherish them,
\q1
\v 2 your ear will be obedient to wisdom,
\q2 you will apply your heart to knowledge and use it to teach your son.
\q1
\v 3 For if you appeal to wisdom
\q2 and cry out for understanding,
\q1
\v 4 and if you search for her like silver
\q2 and seek diligently for her as if for treasure,
\q1
\v 5 then you will understand the fear of the Lord
\q2 and discover the knowledge of God.
\q1
\v 6 For the Lord gives wisdom,
\q2 and from his presence come knowledge and understanding.
\q1
\v 7 He lays up salvation for the upright
\q2 and protects their journey.
\q1
\v 8 He guards the paths of righteousness
\q2 and protects the road for those who fear him.
\q1
\v 9 Then you shall understand righteousness and judgement,
\q2 and will straighten all the right paths.
\q1
\v 10 For if wisdom enters into your understanding
\q2 and insight seems pleasant to your soul,
\q1
\v 11 good advice shall guard you
\q2 and holy understanding shall keep you safe,
\q1
\v 12 delivering you from the path of evil
\q2 and from the man who has nothing trustworthy to say.
\q1
\v 13 Alas for those who leave the right paths
\q2 to walk in the ways of darkness,
\q1
\v 14 who rejoice in evil and delight in wicked perversity,
\q2
\v 15 whose ways are crooked and tracks winding,
\q1
\v 16 who would remove you far from the straight way
\q2 and would divert you from a righteous purpose.
\q1
\v 17 My son, do not let evil counsel overtake you.
\q2 It forsakes the teaching of its youth and forgets the covenant of God.
\q1
\v 18 It has set up house near death
\q2 and its door posts near Hades with its spectres.
\q1
\v 19 All who walk that way shall not return,
\q2 nor shall they find the right paths to regain the years of life.
\q1
\v 20 For had they gone by good ways
\q2 they would have found the smooth paths of righteousness.
\q1
\v 21 The good shall inherit the land,
\q2 the innocent will live there.
\q1 For the upright shall dwell in the land,
\q2 the holy will remain there.
\q1
\v 22 The ways of the ungodly shall disappear from the land
\q2 and the transgressors shall be rooted out.
\c 3
\q1
\v 1 My son, do not forget my law
\q2 but let your heart guard my words.
\q1
\v 2 For length of days and years of life and peace
\q2 shall be added to you.
\q1
\v 3 Do not let mercy and faith forsake you.
\q2 Bind them around your neck and write them on the tablets of your heart.
\q1 By so doing you shall find grace
\q2
\v 4 and think of what is noble in the sight of the Lord and of men.
\q1
\v 5 Trust in the Lord with all your heart
\q2 and do not be exalted in your own estimation.
\q1
\v 6 In all your ways acquaint yourself with her
\q2 so that you may rightly direct your paths, and so that your feet do not stumble.
\q1
\v 7 And do not be wise in your own eyes.
\q2 Fear God and keep yourself from every wickedness.
\q1
\v 8 Then there shall be healing for your body
\q2 and care for your bones.
\q1
\v 9 Honour the Lord with your righteous labours
\q2 and give him the firstfruits of your righteousness,
\q1
\v 10 so that your barns may be filled with abundance of grain
\q2 and your presses overflow with wine.
\q1
\v 11 My son, do not despise the correction of the Lord
\q2 nor faint when you are rebuked by him.
\q1
\v 12 For whom the Lord loves he corrects,
\q2 and he disciplines every son whom he receives.
\q1
\v 13 Blessed is the man who has found wisdom
\q2 and the man who knows discernment,
\q1
\v 14 for it is better to trade for her
\q2 than for treasures of gold and silver.
\q1
\v 15 She is more precious than valuable stones.
\q2 No evil can withstand her.
\q1 She is well known to all those who draw near to her.
\q2 No precious thing is her equal,
\q1
\v 16 for length of days and years of life are in her right hand,
\q2 and in her left hand are riches and glory.
\q1 Out of her mouth proceeds righteousness,
\q2 and she carries law and mercy on her tongue.
\q1
\v 17 Her ways are good ways
\q2 and all her paths are of peace.
\q1
\v 18 She is a tree of life to all those who lay hold of her,
\q2 and she is a protection to those who anchor themselves to her, as to the Lord.
\q1
\v 19 By wisdom God has founded the earth.
\q2 By prudence he has prepared the heavens.
\q1
\v 20 By insight the depths were broken up
\q2 and the clouds dropped rain.
\q1
\v 21 My son, do not let this pass you by.
\q2 Keep my counsel and understanding
\q1
\v 22 so that your soul may live, so that grace may adorn your neck,
\q2 so that your body may be healthy and your bones sound,
\q1
\v 23 so that in all your ways you may walk confidently in peace,
\q2 and so that your foot may not stumble.
\q1
\v 24 For if you sit down, you shall not be dismayed,
\q2 and if you sleep, you shall slumber sweetly.
\q1
\v 25 And you shall not be afraid of terror that comes upon you,
\q2 nor of assaults by ungodly men who come at you,
\q1
\v 26 for the Lord shall oversee all your ways
\q2 and shall establish your feet so that you shall not be moved.
\q1
\v 27 Do not neglect to do good to the needy
\q2 whenever your hand has opportunity to help.
\q1
\v 28 Do not say, “Come back another time. Tomorrow I will give you something,”
\q2 for you do not know what the next day will bring.
\q1
\v 29 Do not devise evils against your friend
\q2 who lives near you and trusts you.
\q1
\v 30 Do not contend with anyone without reason
\q2 lest he do some evil to you.
\q1
\v 31 Do not invite the reproaches of the wicked
\q2 nor imitate their ways.
\q1
\v 32 For every transgressor is unclean in the sight of the Lord;
\q2 he does not sit with the righteous.
\q1
\v 33 The curse of God is in the homes of the ungodly,
\q2 but the dwellings of the just are blessed.
\q1
\v 34 The Lord resists the proud,
\q2 but he gives grace to the humble.
\q1
\v 35 The wise shall inherit glory,
\q2 but the ungodly have exalted dishonour.
\c 4
\q1
\v 1 You children, listen to the instruction of a father
\q2 and pay attention to gain understanding,
\q1
\v 2 for I give you a good gift;
\q2 do not forsake my law.
\q1
\v 3 I too was a son obedient to my father
\q2 and beloved in the eyes of my mother.
\q1
\v 4 She taught me, saying, ‘Let our words be fixed in your heart.
\q2 Keep our commandments; do not forget them
\v 5 nor neglect what I tell you.’
\q1
\v 6 Do not forsake her and she will cleave to you;
\q2 love her and she will watch over you.
\m
\v 7 \f 4:7 \ft No verse 7 \f*
\q1
\v 8 Keep her secure and she will exalt you;
\q2 honour her so that she may embrace you,
\q1
\v 9 so that she may crown your head with graces
\q2 and protect you with a crown of delight.
\q1
\v 10 Listen, my son, and accept what I say,
\q2 and the years of your life will be multiplied and your opportunities many.
\q1
\v 11 For I teach you the ways of wisdom;
\q2 I enable you to take the right paths.
\q1
\v 12 When you walk your steps will be not be restricted
\q2 and when you run you will not tire.
\q1
\v 13 Take hold of my teaching and do not let go of it,
\q2 but keep it by you throughout your life.
\q1
\v 14 Do not walk in the paths of the ungodly
\q2 nor imitate the ways of the transgressors.
\q1
\v 15 Wherever they pitch their tent, do not go there;
\q2 turn away from them and pass them by.
\q1
\v 16 For they cannot sleep unless they have done evil;
\q2 they are denied sleep and they do not slumber.
\q1
\v 17 Their food is the bread of ungodliness
\q2 and they get drunk with the wine of transgression.
\q1
\v 18 The ways of the just shine like the light;
\q2 they walk on and shine until the day fully dawns.
\q1
\v 19 But the ways of the ungodly are dark;
\q2 they do not know that they stumble.
\q1
\v 20 My son, pay attention to what I say
\q2 and open your ears to my words.
\q1
\v 21 In order that your vitality may not fail you,
\q2 keep them in your heart.
\q1
\v 22 For they are life to those who find them
\q2 and healing for all their flesh.
\q1
\v 23 Guard your heart with utmost diligence,
\q2 for life springs from these words.
\q1
\v 24 Throw off perversity of speech
\q2 and distance yourself from lying lips.
\q1
\v 25 Let you eyes look straight ahead,
\q2 and let your eyelids agree with what is just.
\q1
\v 26 Walk a straight road
\q2 and order your ways aright.
\q1
\v 27 Do not turn to the right nor to the left,
\q2 but steer your feet away from an evil path.
\q1 For God knows the paths on the right side,
\q2 but those on the left are crooked.
\q1 He will make your ways straight
\q2 and guide your steps in peace.
\c 5
\q1
\v 1 My son, pay attention to my wisdom
\q2 and bend your ear to hear my words.
\q1
\v 2 In order that you may gain a good understanding
\q2 I command you with the perception of my lips
\q1 to pay no heed to a worthless woman,
\q2
\v 3 for honey drips from the lips of a harlot.
\q1 For a while you find the taste pleasing,
\q2
\v 4 but later you will find her more bitter than gall
\q2 and sharper than a two-edged sword.
\q1
\v 5 Foolish feet lead those who have dealings with her down to Hades, to death,
\q2 for her steps are not firmly fixed.
\q1
\v 6 She does not walk on the paths of life,
\q2 but her ways are slippery and hidden.
\q1
\v 7 Now then, my son, listen to me
\q2 and do not make my words of no effect.
\q1
\v 8 Remove your ways far from hers;
\q2 do not go near the door of her house.
\q1
\v 9 For you would risk giving away your life to others,
\q2 and your very existence to those without mercy.
\q1
\v 10 Strangers may be filled with your strength,
\q2 and everything you work for become the property of strangers.
\q1
\v 11 Finally you will repent when the flesh of your body is exhausted,
\v 12 and you will say,
\q2 ‘How I hated instruction and my heart avoided correction.
\q1
\v 13 I did not listen to the voice of him who instructed me and taught me,
\q2 nor did I bend my ear.
\q1
\v 14 I was on the edge of every evil,
\q2 even in the midst of the congregation and assembly.’
\q1
\v 15 Drink water from your own vessel
\q2 and from the cisterns of your own well.
\q1
\v 16 Do not let the waters from your well be spilt,
\q2 but let them flow into your own channels.
\q1
\v 17 Let them be only for your own,
\q2 and let no stranger share with you.
\q1
\v 18 Let your fountain be for your own
\q2 and rejoice with the wife of your youth.
\q1
\v 19 Let your loving doe and your graceful foal keep you company
\q2 and think of her as your own, to be with you at all times.
\q1 Enjoying her love
\q2 you shall be fully satisfied.
\q1
\v 20 Do not be intimate with a strange woman
\q2 nor fall into the arms of a woman who is not your own,
\q1
\v 21 for the ways of a man are open to the eyes of God
\q2 and he observes all his paths.
\q1
\v 22 Iniquities ensnare a man,
\q2 and everyone is bound with the chains of his own sins.
\q1
\v 23 Such a man dies with the ignorant and forfeits his possessions and wealth.
\q2 He has perished through folly.
\c 6
\q1
\v 1 My son, if you stand surety for your friend
\q2 you will play into the enemy’s hands.
\q1
\v 2 A man’s own lips become a snare for him
\q2 and he is caught out by his own mouth.
\q1
\v 3 My son, do what I tell you and save yourself,
\q2 for on your friend’s account you have fallen into the power of evil.
\q1 Go, do not give up,
\q2 but challenge that friend for whom you have stood surety.
\q1
\v 4 Do not let your eyes close in sleep
\q2 nor your eyelids droop,
\q1
\v 5 but save yourself like a deer from a trap
\q2 or like a bird from a snare.
\q1
\v 6 Go to the ant, you sluggard, and observe.
\q2 Be zealous to study his ways and become wiser than he is.
\q1
\v 7 He has no land to till
\q2 nor anyone to supervise him and is under no master,
\q1
\v 8 yet he prepares food for himself in summer
\q2 and makes abundant provision for winter.
\q1 Or go to the bee and learn how diligent she is
\q2 and how earnestly she does her work.
\q1 Her labours yield health-giving nourishment for kings and for the common people,
\q2 and she is loved and honoured by all.
\q1 Though she has little strength,
\q2 she leads the way in honouring wisdom.
\q1
\v 9 How long will you lie in bed, you sluggard?
\q2 When will you rise from your slumbers?
\q1
\v 10 You sleep a little, rest a little, then snooze for a short time;
\q2 and then you fold your arms for a while.
\q1
\v 11 Then poverty comes upon you like an evil visitor,
\q2 and destitution arrives like a swift runner.
\q1 But if you are diligent your harvest will rise up as an outpouring
\q2 and poverty, like an evil runner, shall flee from you.
\q1
\v 12 A foolish man, a transgressor,
\q2 walks in ways that are not good.
\q1
\v 13 He winks his eye, makes a sign with his foot
\q2 and gives directions with a snap of his fingers;
\q1
\v 14 with a perverse heart he devises evils continually.
\q2 Such a one causes trouble in the city.
\q1
\v 15 His destruction therefore strikes suddenly,
\q2 overthrow and irretrievable ruin,
\q1
\v 16 for he rejoices in everything that God hates.
\q2 He is ruined by the uncleanness of his soul,
\q1
\v 17 the arrogant eye, the wicked tongue,
\q2 the hands that shed righteous blood,
\q1
\v 18 the heart that devises evil thoughts
\q2 and the feet that hasten to do evil.
\q1
\v 19 A false witness kindles injustice
\q2 and sparks quarrels between brethren.
\q1
\v 20 My son, keep your father’s rules
\q2 and do not reject the advice of your mother.
\q1
\v 21 Bind them to your soul continually,
\q2 and hang them around your neck like a necklace.
\q1
\v 22 Whenever you travel, bring it along, keep it with you;
\q2 and when you sleep, let it guard you so that it is with you when you wake.
\q1
\v 23 For a commandment of the law is a lamp and a light,
\q2 a way of life and a caution and correction.
\q1
\v 24 Keep away from a married woman
\q2 and from the slanderous tongue of a strange woman.
\q1
\v 25 Do not allow lust for a beautiful woman to get the better of you
\q2 nor get caught by the eyes or captivated with her eyelids,
\q1
\v 26 for the value of a harlot is only one loaf
\q2 and a woman hunts for the precious souls of men.
\q1
\v 27 How could anyone bind fire to his bosom
